Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high or oven to 500 degrees. Bring a
large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Mince or grate @garlic{4%cloves}. Roughly
chop @parsley{¼%ounce}. Once water is boiling, add @macaroni pasta{12%ounce} to
pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Drain.

Place @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #small bowl{}. Microwave on high until melted,
about ~{20%seconds}.

> Alternatively, melt butter in a small pan.

Add @panko breadcrumbs{½%cup} and half the parsley to bowl and stir to combine.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%teaspoon} in a large, tall-sided #pan{} over
medium-high heat (use an ovenproof pan if you have one). Add @pancetta{4%ounce}
and cook, tossing, until crisp, ~{4-5%minutes}. Transfer to a paper-towel lined
#plate{} with a #slotted spoon{}, keeping as much oil in pan as possible.

Lower heat under pan to medium. Add garlic and cook until fragrant, about
~{30%seconds}. Add @flour{2%tablespoon} and cook, stirring constantly, until it
loses its raw smell, about ~{1%minute}. Slowly pour in @milk{2%cup}, whisking
vigorously to incorporate. Bring to a gentle boil and cook until thickened,
~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from heat, then add @parmesan cheese{½%cup} and stir until
melted.

Add @crushed tomatoes{1%box} and @spinach{5%ounce} to pan. Stir to wilt spinach 
(if leaves do not wilt, return pan to medium heat). Season with salt and pepper.
Stir in drained macaroni, pancetta, and remaining parsley. Season with salt and
pepper.

> If your pan is not ovenproof, transfer mixture to a small baking dish at this point.

Sprinkle crust mixture over top of pasta. Broil or bake until crust is golden,
~{2-3%minutes}. Divide pasta between plates and serve.